SIMPLE: meander
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Meander
<hw>Me*an"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Maeander</ets>, orig., a river in Phrygia, proverbial for its many
windings, Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>m⟦eacute⟧andre</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A winding, crooked, or involved course; <as>as, the
<ex>meanders</ex> of the veins and arteries</as>.</def> <rj><au>Sir M.
Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While lingering rivers in <qex>meanders</qex> glide.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir R. Blackmore.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A tortuous or intricate movement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Fretwork. See
<er>Fret</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meander</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Meander
<hw>Me*an"der</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To wind, turn, or twist; to
make flexuous.</def> <rj><qau>Dryton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meander</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Meander
<hw>Me*an"der</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Meandered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Meandering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To wind or turn in a course or
passage; to be intricate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Five miles <qex>meandering</qex> with a mazy motion⟦br⟧
Through wood and dale the sacred river ran.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meandrian</ent>⟦br⟧
